South African Equities: AngloGold, Gold Fields, Remgro, Simeka

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-02-25T16:27:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-25/south-african-equity-market-massmart-murray-roberts-simeka.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index snapped three days of losses, gaining 259.12, or 0.8
percent, to 31,965.59 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg,
limiting the week’s loss to 1.7 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    AngloGold Ashanti Ltd . (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest producer
of the precious metal, retreated for a second day, falling 5.32
rand, to 338.45 rand. The South African government wants mining
companies to contribute toward the costs of treating acid water,
which is oozing out of derelict gold mines around Johannesburg.
Costs are estimated to be an initial capital outlay of 443
million rand ($62.6 million) and a further 76 million rand
annually, the Department for Water Affairs said in a report
today.    Gold Fields Ltd . (GFI SJ), the continent’s second-largest
producer of gold, dropped for a fourth day, losing 1.84 rand, or
1.5 percent, to 122.01 rand while Harmony Gold Mining Company
Ltd. (HAR SJ) fell 0.7 percent to 80.71 rand.  Insimbi Refractory & Alloy Supplies Ltd. (ISB SJ), a
foundry-supplies company, advanced the most since Dec. 1,
gaining 4 cents, or 8.7 percent, to 50 cents. The company
withdrew a cautionary notice and said it had terminated
unspecified discussions. It did not give any more details.    RMB Holdings Ltd . (RMH SJ), an investment company, climbed
the most since Dec. 15, rising 1.08 rand, or 2.9 percent, to
38.35 rand. The company said the only outstanding condition of
its purchase of  FirstRand Ltd .’s (FSR SJ) 45 percent stake in
property and casualty insurer OUTsurance is approval from the
country’s short- and long-term insurance registrar. FirstRand
increased 2.6 percent, to 19.51 rand.    Remgro Ltd . (REM SJ), an investment holding company, jumped
the most since Sept. 20, advancing 3.3 percent, or 3.59 rand, to
113.25 rand. Remgro holds is the single largest shareholder in
RMH Holdings.    Simeka Business Group Ltd . (SBG SJ), a computer-hardware
and support company, rose for the first time in six days,
gaining 2 cents, or 12 percent, to 19 cents. Simeka returned to
profit in the first half through November, posting net income of
30 million rand ($4.2 million) compared with a loss of 158.9
million rand a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
